{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958050201/0252.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nUNION JOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, May 2,1958\nUnhappy Record\nTHE NUMBER of unemployed Ohio\nworkers receiving unemployment com\npensation jumped to a new all-time high\nunder the Ohio compensation law last\nweek when the total hit 221, 422.\nThis figure, of course, does not tell the\nentire story. There are many jobless work\ners who are not protected by unemploy\nment compensation, and therefore the\n221,422 must be regarded as a minimum\nfigure.\nSome 302,000 persons are seeking work\nthrough State employment offices. Some\nof these people have jobs but are looking\nfor other work. However, it is safe to esti\nmate unemployment in Ohio as close to the\n300,000 mark.\nAnother statistic that will become more\nsignificant in the days ahead is the num\nber of unemployed who have exhausted\ntheir weeks of compensation. In the first\nthree months of this year, 17,500 workers\nexhausted their compensation.\nThese latest figures are an unhappy\ncommentary on the state of Ohio\u2019s econ\nomy and the unfortunate plight of Ohio\u2019s\nunemployed. The statistics also are an in\ndictment of the failure of the state to do\nsomething about it.\nBank\nSings\nNew Tune\nI\nT DOESN\u2019T HAPPEN often\u2014in fact, it\u2019s\ndarn rare\u2014that you find a bank say\ning the same thing Labor has been saying\nfor some time about the shortcomings of\nOhio\u2019s unemployment compensation law.\nBut it happened on April 13, during\nthe weekly radio program sponsored by\nthe Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland.\nThe subject of the broadcast was unem\nployment compensation \u201cas abusiness\nstabilizer.\u201d\nThe Bank noted that unemployment\ncompensation has \u201cdeparted somewhat\u201d\nfrom its original purpose of bolstering con\nsumer demand during times of substantial\nunemployment. This has resulted from\nseveral factors, it explained.\nOne of the factors, it stated, is that\n\u201cthe scale of unemployment compensa\ntion benefits has not been increased as fast\nas wages have moved up, so that weekly\nbenefits paid now amount to a smaller\nproportion of average wages than they\ndid several years ago.\u201d\nIt also pointed out that the average\ncompensation payment today is \"consider\nably lass than one-half of average weekly\nearnings which is often suggested as the\ndesirable percentage.\u201d\nAnother factor that has served to\nweaken the Ohio law is \u201cthat it is more\ndifficult for an unemployed person to qual\nify as a beneficiary than it was when the\nsystem was first organized.\u201d This, it ex\nplained, is because \u201cunemployment com\npensation programs have become increas\ningly restrictive in their eligibility and\ndisqualification requirements.\u201d\nWhat the Bank didn\u2019t say is that the\nsorry state of the Ohio law is the handi\nwork of the same selfish groups that have\nfought every piece of legislation designed\nto help protect the workers in time of mis\nfortune.\nIt could have noted that the Ohio\nChamber of Commerce was against the en\nactment of any unemployment compensa\ntion law and if the Chamber had had its\nway back in the 3Q\u2019s, jobless Ohio work\ners today would be receiving no financial\nhelp at all!\nThe fact that Ohio\u2019s unemployment\ncompensation law is a shambles today is\nan unfortunate symbol of the political in\nfluence of the Ohio Chamber of Commerce\nwith the State Legislature.\nNow, wouldn\u2019t it be something if a\nBank said that some day!\nMerger to the Rescue\nTHE FORTHCOMING merger of the\ntwo Houses of Labor in Ohio is com\ning to the rescue in the nick of time.\nA united group, speaking determinedly\nfor more than a million Ohio union work\ners, may be the only force strong enough\nto send the anti-union pests crawling back\nbehind the woodwork.\nIn several ways, 1958 seems to be a\ncrucial year in the affairs of organized la\nbor in Ohio. Many issues\u2014such as the\nSUB, the compulsory open shop proposal,\nand the inhuman unemployment compen\nsation laws\u2014all seem to be coming to a\nhead at the same time.\nIn the Journal\u2019s opinion, the best news\nof all is the fact that a mighty, unified or\nganization of labor is being created in\nOhio to meet these issues head-on.\nWealthy But Stingy\nVERY SO OFTEN you read something\nA about Ohio\u2019s great wealth and how\nlucky we all are to be living within its\nwealthy boundaries.\nNaturally it\u2019s nice to read such words.\nBut it\u2019s unfortunate that they fail to tell\nthe true story of life for a great many peo\nple who are being short-changed within\nthose boundaries.\nIn recent days, Ohio\u2019s mental hospitals\nhave been branded as \u201cverminous fire\ntraps in which poorly fed patients have\nlittle hope of recovery.\u201d At the same time,\nstate officials announced a $6-million cut\nback in the mental health program.\nOhio ranks 27th among the states in\nmoney spent for the care of each mental\npatient. Ohio\u2019s Mental Hygiene Commis\nsioner, Dr. Joseph E. Duty, told an AFL\nCIO audience last week that Ohio \u201cis not\nup to its rightful place among the 48\nstates\u201d in its support of mental hospitals.\nRecent rankings of the states by the\nNational Education Association discloses\nthat Ohio ranks 28th in the amount of\nmoney it spends for each pupil in the pub\nlic schools; 19th in teachers\u2019 salaries and\n31st in per capital spending for education.\nOhio has inadequate facilities for the\nhousing and rehabilitation of its prison\npopulation. Twice the number of men be\nhind bars at the close of World War II may\nbe in Ohio prisons before the end of 1960.\nState officials say they must ask for $12\n$15 million to build another badly needed\ninstitution.\nOhio continued to require its aged and\nneedy to get by on $65 a month. It has not\nincreased unemployment compensation\nsince 1955, forcing the jobless to attempt\nto live on a weekly maximum of $33, plus\na possible $3 a week for no more than two\ndependents.\nFacts such as the above make us won\nder: If Ohio is really a wealthy state, why\ndo we rank so far down the list in support\nof our schools, teachers and mental health\nprogram? Why don\u2019t we give the old folks\nthe help they really need? Why doesn\u2019t\nOhio pay decent compensation to its job\nless?\nIn brief then, one is certainly justified\nin wondering: If Ohio\u2019s so wealthy, who\u2019s\n1\ngot all the wealth? We know who ain\u2019t\ngot it! 1\nThe Modest Subsidizers\nT\nHE NATIONAL ASSOCIATION of\nManufacturers has been caught with\nits \u201cpublic interest\u201d slip showing.\nAs part of its well-financed, unending\ncampaign to sway American public opin\nion to the cause of virulent anti-unionism\ni t h a s conducted numerous undercover\nprograms. Its latest escapade has been to\nprovide television kinescopes of the Mc\nClellan Committee\u2019s hearings on the Koh\nler strike to 27 TV stations without charge\nand without claiming credit for the group\nproviding the free films.\nThe NAM\u2019s apparently unaccountable\nmodesty in shielding the fact that it paid\nfor the films shown by the TV stations is\nperhaps better understood in light of the\npublic\u2019s general disdain for the NAM and\nits avowed goals.\nBut the NAM\u2019s modesty in this case is\nof perhaps more public interest than the\nfilms it so quietly subsidized; a violation\nof the Federal Communications Act by\nthe TV stations may be involved. The FCC\nshould initiate an immediate investiga\nte establish facts about the NAM\u2019s efforts\nto sway public opinion without disclosing\nits identity.\nTHE U. S. LABOR Department reports\nthe number of persons drawing unemploy\nment compensation rose to 3,314,307 in\nthe week ended April 5 This is the\nhighest in the 19 years of the Federal\nState program.\nBUSINESS WEEK magazine writes this\nweek: \u201cFew economists in Washington see\nbetter times before November, when the\nCongressional elections roll around, no\nmatter what Washington does.\u201d\nIOWA GOV. Herschel Loveless: \u201cIn\nthe days of Theodore Roosevelt, the Re\npublicans had a famous slogan, \u2018Speak\nsoftly and carry a big stick.\u2019 The slogan of\nthe present Administration is, \u2018Ask Sher\nman Adams and hand me my golf clubs\u2019.1\nTHE GOVERNMENT reports that 37\nper cent of American families had incomes\nof less than $4,000 in 1957 and 14 per cent\nhad less than $2,000.\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\nFIFTEEN YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 30, 1948: Spearheading a drive for a\nconstitutional ban on the union shop, the Flor\nida house of representatives approved by a\nvote of 68 to 52 a constitutional amendment\noutlawing union security in this state\nSpicer workers decided to abide by the \u201cno\nstrike for the duration\u201d policy of the Interna\ntional UAW when they voted decisively not\nto strike in the two days of balloting conducted\nat Local 12 headquarters April 26 and 27.\nTEN YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 29, 1948: Despite several good clues\nand questioning of a Detroit suspect, the at\ntacker who shot UAW-CIO President Walter\nReuther in his home April 20 remains at large\nA total of $10,904.60 has been donated to\nthe Local 12 Summer Camp at Sand Lake to\nimprove and expand the camp.\nFIVE YEARS AGO\nMAY 1, 1953: Members of the American\nFloor Surfacing Unit of Local 12, UAW-CIO,\nratified a new agreement ending a nine-week\nstrike Toledo had 62 UAW delegates at the\nCIO legislative session in Columbus last week\nwhich was sponsored by the State CIO Coun\ncil. The purpose of the conference was to see\nvarious committees on bills introduced in the\nGeneral Assembly. Separate meetings were ar\nranged for the delegates with senators and\nrepresentatives.\n\u2018Keep the Pot Boiling, Boys!\u2019\nI\n0\nr\nd\n\n\n1\nw (s\nt\n3\n\nwoaxe\"N\nI\nCITY MANAGER i\nLEAGUE\nGREENHILLJ\n4\nL\n>3'\na.\n(CLLAY-orrsts\nHEF=\n(RNGMr\n(CLMsok\n6-===\nLASALLE mi\n\"Ax cor\nl\ndeeLEss Alb\nASUs\nThink It Over\nNMIUIIM\nofC\na\ns*\nGay\nIWTIITTMWWTTNFORM\n'An Expensive Luxury'\niimHitniiuitiiHiuMmu\nBy PETE ZVARA\nammminaimAW***\nmm\nA\nDDRESSING THE U. S. Chamber of Com\nmerce in Washington a few days ago, Mr.\nAllen W. Dulles, director of the Central Intel\nligence Agency, made the very somber yet\nvery true observation that \u201ca recession is an\nexpensive luxury.\u201d\nAnd it certainly is. For even a modicum of\nserious thinking must convince anyone that\nthe forced idleness of nearly six million work\ners, plus the partial unemployment of an addi\ntion 3.5 million more workers must cost our\neconomy, our people and our country untold\nbillions of dollars worth of goods and services.\nIn his speech, Mr. Dulles\ndid not restrict himself to\ngeneralities. He made some\nvery specific and certainly\npertinent points. And he\nshould know his facts since\nhe heads one of the most far\nflung intelligence networks\nin all history.\nSpecifically, Mr. Dulles\nmade reference to the giant\nstrides of Soviet economy as\nagainst the decline of our\nown. For the first time in\nt\nPete Zvara\nhistory, he pointed out, steel production in the\nCommunist world forged ahead of ours during\nthe first three months of this year. He further\npointed out that while Soviet industrial out\nput gained 11 per cent last year over the\nprevious year, our own factory production de\nclined by 11 per cent.\nOf course, the communists make much ado\nabout these figures in their ceaseless propa\nganda war against us. But what is more fright\nening is the fact that unless our economy, our\nindustries perk up and take on this new chal\nlenge, our free enterprise system will suffer\nserious drawbacks in the market places of the\nworld. Mr. Dulles expressed the opinion that\nthe Soviet Union will avoid war with the\nUnited States, but will intensify its cold war\nwaged against us on the economic front.\nCERTAINLY THERE is plenty of evidence\nto support the thinking and fears of Mr.\nDulles. Just last week, for example, the West\nGerman government entered into a trade\nagreement with Moaeow calling for an annual\ntrade between the two countries of around\n$300 million, and with the pact running for\nthree years, the total amount involved in this\none pact alone runs close to a billion dollars.\nThat\u2019s a lot of trading anywhere. And, the\nway it looks, it is just a beginning.\nFor what can happen between Germany\nand the Soviet Union may, and most likely\nwill take place on a greater or lesser scale,\nbetween the Communist nations and the coun\ntries of the Western or Non-Communist World.\nThis brings to mind the trip that Vice\nPresident Richard Nixon is making at this\nvery moment to about eight different South\nAmerican nations. It is known that Soviet\ntrade has been penetrating into these coun\ntries. heretofore almost an exclusive preserve\nfor American exports. Reportedly Mr. Nixon's\njob is to mend our political and export fences\nin these Latin American countries and to pre\nvent further penetration by the Soviets.\nThe far ranging scope of the export-import\ntrade challenge of the Soviet Union can be\nfurther measured by the steady, almost specta\ncular growth of the Communist economic and\nindustrial complex. According to Mr. Dulles,\nRussia's gross national product, the total of\ngoods and services produced, may total 50%\nof our own G. N. P. in 1962. As The Wall\nStreet Journal reports Mr. Dulles\u2019 remarks,\n\u201cthis figure would be up from 33% in 1955\nand about 40% in 1956.\"\nNo wonder he, Mr. Dulles, regards this\nsituation as \u201cthe most serious challenge this\ncountry has ever faced in time of peace.\u201d\nWELL, SINCE all of this is no secret, what\nare we doing about this challenge, this \u201cmen\nace,\u201d as Mr. Duller calls it? Judging from an\nappraisal of the current situation by President\nGeorge Meany of the AFL-CIO a few days ago,\nnot very much. President Meany expressed\nthe fear that our recession is sliding into a\nreal depression. He predicted, following a\nmeeting of the AFL-CIO general executive\nboard, that by June our jobless will number\nsix million, with another 3.5 million workers\ndoing part-time work.\n\u201cThe recession is a depression already for\nthe 5,200,000 unemployed and the 3.5 million\npart-time workers counted last March,\u201d Mr.\nMeany said.\nAnd then, speaking for some fifteen mil\nlion organized workers, President Meany\ncalled upon the Congress and the White House\nto cut taxes immediately by 6 to 8 billion dol\nlars for the low and middle income families\nand to increase jobless pay benefits without\nfurther delay. In addition the AFL-CIO leaders\nurged the government to take whatever other\nsteps are necessary to get us out of the reces\nsion and to live up to the 1946 Employment\nAct that places the responsibility for promot\ning maximum employment, production and\npurchasing power squarely upon our federal\ngovernment.\nPresident Meany scored both the Eisen\nhower Administration and the Democratic\nCongress for failure to live up to their respon\nsibilities to halt the recession.\nWhat was it that Soviet Premier Nikita\nKhrushchev said about two weeks ago to Mr.\nL. Thompson, U. S. Ambassador to Moscow,\nat a Polish Embassy reception? Mr. Khrush\nchev was gayly taunting the American Am\nbassador about the developing economic com\npetition between the East and the West. This\nis the way The New York Times reports the\nincident:\n\u201cLet\u2019s agree on this, Mr. Thompson,\u201d the\nSoviet Premier said in one of his folksy\nwide-ranging talks. \u201cWhen we win this com\npetition we shall also re-educate you. We\nBolsheviks are ravenous people. What we\nachieved through struggles in the past is\nnot sufficient for us. We want more\u2014tomor\nrow. Mr. Thompson, watch out. We're step\nping on your tail.\u201d\nSurely these are ominous words, full of\nportent. The challenge is clear and unmistak\nable. It would be stupid to try to ignore it.\nThe truth of the matter is that we cannot\nignore it even if we Wished to do so. We can\nbeat the Soviet challenge on every front But\nwe can\u2019t do it with our economy limping along\nin low gear. Our economy must slip into high\ngear, and that means full employment, full\nproduction and high purchasing power for our\npeople. It means an ever increasing foreign\ntrade on every front, with every nation on the\nface of this Earth. If this is not done and\ndone very quickly for time is fast slipping by,\nMr. Khrushchev\u2019s taunt about \u201cburying you\u201d\n\u2014meaning us\u2014 will become much more than\na symbolic threat.\nAnd the real tragedy will be that we shall\nbe our own stupid grave diggers.\nWHILE THE prime responsibility for lead\ning us out of Ulis recession lies with the\nEisenhower Republican Administration and the\nCongress, yet we the people must also play our\npart in this epic struggle. A first class opport\nunity in this respect will be presented to us\nnext Tuesday on primary election day. It\nshould be the prime responsibility of every\ncitizen to cast his vote for the candidates and\nissues of his choice. Our choice may differ.\nHowever that may be, the least we can do is\nVOTE ON TUESDAY.\nORGAPilll TOLEDO 100%\nOffictal Publication of Organised Labor\nla Northwestern Ohio\nGrand\nAward\nWinner\nCatered at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 14. ISIS\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 414 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phene CB. 1-9126\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nWilliam Borden\nDerate Collins..\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nse0e0000000000ce*\nEditor\nAsseetato Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nEdmond A. Pawlick! Journal Cameramen\nWalter Murphy, Charles Ballard,\nOtto Beebe (Local 348) Board of Trustees\nDave Huber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCB. 4-4400 and CB. 41141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N. x.\nt\nONE OF THE MOST important cushions the New Deal\nprovided against the painful shocks of a drop in\nthe U.S. economy was unemployment compensation. The\nfight to get that social legislation through Congress and\npast state legislatures was often hard and bitter. But,\nnow, as seems almost always to be the case with progres\nsive legislation once it\u2019s an accomplished fact, we take\na comfortable pride in the unemployment compensation\nlaws.\nA Republican President so far agrees with their im\nportance during a recessionary period that he even sug\ngests that the states lengthen by 50 per cent the number\nof weeks in which jobless workers may collect these bene\nfits, with money, Mr. Eisenhower thriftily proposes, bor\nrowed from the federal government.\nHowever, an unpleasant truth is being widely 'dis\nregarded. Our present unemployment compensation\nlaws are out of date. The sums provided by them are\ntotally inadequate.\nIn 1939, when the duration of benefits, and the\namount of those benefits, were fixed, they were reason\nably generous. Though there are, and were, great dif\nferences in different states, an American who lost his job\nin \u201939 could look forward to collecting all the way from\n50 to 90 per cent of the prevailing pay scale in his state.\nAll that has changed. As none of us needs to be re\nminded, the cost of living, between 1939 and 1957, has\nskyrocketed. With few exceptions, the scale of jobless\nbenefits has undergone harefly any change at all.\nThe original cushion against economic distress has\nshrunk to the thinness of straw pallet in an old-time\ncounty jail. All of us\u2014the jobless of course most of all\n\u2014are, therefore, now suffering from the persistent re\nfusal of state legislatures, of business organizations, and\nof Congress during the years of prosperity to lift those\nlevels when it would have been easiest to lift them.\nBut what was not done yesterday we cannot, as a na\ntion, afford to put off until tomorrow. Poverty, it\u2019s been\nsaid more often than it\u2019s been believed, is the most con\ntagious of diseases. Americans cannot blandly accept that\nmisfortune to its jobless citizens, quite simply, for selfish\nreasons.\nLetters To The Editor\nPraises\nUnion\nTO THE EDITOR:\nI am one of the unfortunate\nunemployed persons in Toledo\nwho sits and wonders why this\ngreat nation which spends bil\nlions for overseas aid cannot\nprovide Jobs for our own peo\nple.\nA nation which cannot pro\nvide for her own people can\nnot hope for peace in the\nworld when there is unrest in\nher own back yard. Lincoln\nsaid that this wonderful na\ntion shall never perish from\nwithout but from within. I\noften wonder if this can be the\ngroundwork for that. I pray\nGod we stay free and that\nsomehow they wake up in\nWashington.\nA word about SUB. I can\nnot understand the Governor\nof Ohio taking the position he\ndoes. The state will not lose a\ndime in money and still he\nfights it I myself am going to\nvote for a good man, not one\nwho goes around playing golf\nor vacationing.\nAlthough I\u2019m laid off I\nwon\u2019t vote for any \u201cRight-to\nWork\u201d law. It smells like it\u2019s\ncoming from high Republi\ncans. Pray God 1960 comes\npretty fast. Vote Democratic.\nGod bless the Union.\nA FRIEND\nEDITOR'S NOTE: The Jour\nnal does not follow the policy\nof printing anonymous letters\nbut because of the sincerity\nand sentiments expressed by\nthe writer, made an exception\nin this case.\nBulletin Board\nSaturday, May 3\nKIDS PARTY\u201410:00 A.M \u2014Parlor A\nE. W. BLISS\u20141:30 P.M.\u2014Parlor A\nSTEEL TUBE\u201410:00 A.M.\u2014Parlor C\nSunday, May 4\nt\nSPICER STEWARDS\u20148:30 A.M.\u2014Parlor A\nSPICER MEMBERS\u201410:00 A.M.\u2014Parlor A\nPETERS STAMPING\u20142:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor B\nJ&L ELECTION\u201410:00 A.M. to 4 P.M.\u2014Parlor C\nMATHER\u201410:00 A.M.\u2014Parlor H\nMonday, May 5\nTOLEDO WIRE PROD.\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor c\nTuesday, May G _\nTILLOTSON\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor A\nENSIGN\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor B\nSTANDARD EQUIPMENT\u20147 30 P.M.\u2014Parlor C\nPIPE THREADING OFFICE\u20147:30 P.M.\u2014Parlor H\nWednesday, May 7\nDEVILBISS\u20147:30 P.M.\u2014Parlor A\nINT. HARVESTER\u20145:30 P.M.\u2014Parlor B\nTILLOTSON\u20141:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor B\nT.U.J. CIRCULATION\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor C\nALLIED WHEEL\u20144:15 P.M.\u2014Parlor H\nThursday, May 3\nWOMEN\u2019S GUILD\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor A\u2014\nACME\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor B\nCAMERA CLUB\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor C\nCAMP COUNSELLORS\u20147:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor H\nDARLING\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Room 309\nFriday, May 9\nLOCAL* 12\u20148:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor A\nBOARD OF GOVERNORS\u20147:00 P.M.\u2014Parlor B\nPHOTO ENGRAVERS\n2nd Monday 5:30 PM 612% Huron St\nBOOKBINDERS\n2nd Thursday 7 P.M. 912 Adams St\nRETAIL CLERKS\n1st Wednesday 8 P.M. 215% Summit St.\nMAILERS\n3rd Monday 6 P-M. 612%4 Huron St.\n4.\nCOMMUNICATION WORKERS. LOCAL 4319\n2nd Thursday 8 P.M. 612 First St","height":"26836","width":"19496"}}
